    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36.14"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">14</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        311 Westfield Drive 
                        O Fallon, Illinois
                        February 1st, 1972
                    </dateline>
                    
                    Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G</hi> Neihardt 
                    Nebraska's Poet-Laureate
                
                    <salute>Wonderful Sir:</salute> 
                </opener>
                <p>This letter has been written by my heart repeatedly for over 40 years, beginning when I studied the <hi rend="underline">Song of the Indian Wars</hi> in <unclear>Winside</unclear> High School.</p>
                
                <p>Congratulations on your recent birthday. I was in Wayne <add>^last May</add> a short space after yoiu gave your wonderful address at Wayne State College, but I was not there in time.</p>
                
                <p>How much money would my 75 eighth grade history students have to raise to finance you to come to Marissa, Ill. (32 miles from St. Louis) so that you could thrill their hearts and mine at graduation time <del>in May</del> the 1st day of June 1972?</p> 
                
                <p>Tonight I read <hi rend="underline">The Song of the Messiah,</hi> 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36.15"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                    and I couldn't refrain from writing. Thank you for your great gifts to America.</p> 
                
                <p>I am Paul Harrington's wife's 1st cousin, once removed. Ella Harrington was my father's 1st cousin. My great-grand-father rode the Wayne &amp; Dixon county prairies in 1869 &#8212; George Ives King, a retired Union Army Chaplain. I belive you knew Paul. Ella still lives in Wayne and I saw her last May, there.</p> 
                
                <p>Thousands of times I have urged your works to people. It is a stirring, heartfelt epic &#8212; thank you again &#8212; so very much.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>John McCabe Moore</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
